# This defines valid Plasm syntax for this prompt; reply with one valid plasm_program:
#
# Output choice:
# - Use a single `plasm_expr` only for one direct lookup/read/search/relation/method/action whose result is already the answer.
# - For **compositional** work (multiple steps, joins, reporting, summarization, writes, or any structured textual payload—markdown, HTML, plain text, JSON text, CSV-like lines, etc.), use a **multi-line `plasm_program`** by default—do not chain many one-line `plasm` calls.
# - Prefer a multi-line `plasm_program` for imperative/analytical/reporting goals: bind inputs, narrow with `projection` and `postfix` (including `transform` and bracket/heredoc tails), then return a small synthesized result.
#
# Syntax contract (pseudo-EBNF; TSV rows bind the catalogue-specific `plasm_expr` atoms):
# plasm_program ::= plasm_roots | binding+ plasm_roots
# binding       ::= ident "=" plasm_node
# plasm_roots   ::= plasm_return ("," plasm_return)*
# plasm_return  ::= node_ref | plasm_expr
# plasm_node    ::= ( plasm_expr | node_ref ) postfix* | node_ref "=>" plasm_value | node_ref "=>" effect_expr
# plasm_expr    ::= entity_expr [projection]
# entity_expr   ::= query_all | get | query | relation | method | create_action
# query_all     ::= e#
# get           ::= e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v)
# query         ::= e#{p#=v, …}
# relation      ::= e#(id).p#
# method        ::= e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..)
# create_action ::= e#.m#(args)
# projection    ::= e#(id)[p#,…] | "[" fields "]"
# postfix       ::= transform | "[" fields "]" | "[" fields "]" heredoc
# positive_int  ::= non-zero decimal integer literal
# agg_func      ::= "sum" | "avg" | "min" | "max"
# agg_spec      ::= ident "=" ( "count" | agg_func "(" field ")" )
# agg_specs     ::= agg_spec ("," agg_spec)*
# sort_dir      ::= omitted | "desc" | "asc" | "ascending" | "descending"
# transform     ::= ".limit(" positive_int ")" | ".sort(" field ["," sort_dir] ")" | ".aggregate(" agg_specs ")" | ".group_by(" field "," agg_specs ")" | ".singleton()" | ".page_size(" positive_int ")"
# fields        ::= [p#,…]
# plasm_value   ::= literal | node_ref | node_ref.field | _.field | [v, …]
# effect_expr   ::= taught write/update/delete/action surface from DOMAIN (same line may template rows)
# ident/node_ref/field ::= agent-chosen names for bound nodes and fields
# literal      ::= quoted string | number | bool | null | heredoc
#
# Examples (illustrations only; `agg_spec` / `agg_specs` / `transform` above are authoritative):
# - `.aggregate(n=count)`, `.aggregate(total=sum(amount), lo=min(price))`, `.group_by(author, n=count)`.
#
# Node-ref continuation:
# - **`postfix`** (see `postfix` and `transform` above) applies to the same surface expression as `plasm_expr`; you may chain suffixes on one line without an intermediate binding when they attach to that expression (e.g. `e1{…}.limit(20)`).
# - When `ident` is bound to a **surface Plasm** row (get/query/relation result), writing `ident.<relation>` on the RHS continues that row’s expression—the compiler substitutes the bound anchor text and records a dependency on `ident`. Semantics match **repeating the full taught `plasm_expr` for that binding** and appending `.<relation>`. **Compute-only** steps (`projection`, `transform`, derive `=>`, …) are **not** relation anchors: do not append `ident.<relation>` after them—repeat the full expression from DOMAIN or bind a fresh surface node first.
# - **`[fields] <<TAG … TAG`** is postfix like `.limit`: suffix it after the expression whose projected **`rows`** you want to render (Minijinja); see **Bracket render / synthesis** below.
#
# Program construction discipline:
# - **MCP `program` newline contract (read first):** For **compositional** work—anything that is **not** a single taught `plasm_expr` on one physical line—you MUST put **literal newline characters (U+000A)** in the JSON `program` string between physical lines: **one line per `ident = …` binding**, then final bare roots on their own line(s). **Spaces do not separate statements.** If you would write two bindings side-by-side with only spaces, that shape is **always wrong**; split with `
# ` before calling `plasm` / `plasm_run`. (Single-expression calls and single-line heredocs already satisfy this; multi-binding programs are where agents most often flatten incorrectly.)
# - Plan before executing: choose the final answer shape first, then bind only the necessary intermediate nodes.
# - Prefer narrowing with `projection` and `postfix` (including `transform`) and heredoc render tails over returning raw broad lists.
# - When **summarizing or formatting rows from queries/relations in this program**, prefer **bracket-render** (`…[fields] <<TAG …`) so the plan owns the transformation; **static** tagged heredocs remain appropriate for **fixed** payloads not derived from those rows.
# - Return at most small final roots unless the user explicitly asks for raw rows.
# - Use `page(sN_pgM)` only to continue a previously chosen list, not as exploratory browsing.
# - Do not perform probe calls whose only purpose is to inspect shape; the DOMAIN table is the contract.
# - MCP tool `plasm`: the JSON `program` field is one string that may include literal newlines (U+000A). For a `plasm_program`, write one physical line per `ident = …` binding and final bare roots on their own line(s)—**never** one space-concatenated line for multiple bindings. A **tagged heredoc** is still **one logical statement**: after `<<TAG` you must have a newline immediately after `TAG` on the opener line, then the body lines, then a closing line whose trimmed text is `TAG` (or `TAG)` / `TAG,` / `TAG}` on that line). That spans multiple physical lines—**do not** squash `<<TAG` onto the same line as the body.
# - **Final roots** may be comma-separated on one line **or** split across lines; commas **inside** a heredoc body never separate roots. Example: `e1.m2(p3=<<B
# Hello
# B
# ), e2` (comma after the heredoc closes on its `B` line, then the next root).
#
# Catalogue rules:
# - TSV `plasm_expr` cells teach executable catalogue atoms; `Meaning` explains how to choose and fill them.
# - Final program roots are **bare** comma-separated `plasm_expr` / `node_ref` lines (e.g. `e1, e2{...}`); do **not** prefix with `return` — that word is not Plasm syntax.
# - Never paste `Meaning`. Compose taught atoms with bindings/final roots only when a program is needed.
# - All semantic symbols you use must be taught in this prompt.
# - Projection uses a minimal non-empty subset from `[p#,…]`; the identity row teaches the full set once.
# - Leading `p#` rows are metadata for slots when `args:` on a method line is not enough.
#
#   - e#, m#, p# are session-local aliases. Use the aliases **exactly** as shown in expression cells.
# - Pick rows by `Meaning`, then copy the `plasm_expr` shape. Bind args by keyed slot (`p12=value`), never by position or by renumbering.
# - Aliases are session-local. If a new prompt teaches new aliases, discard older e#/m#/p# meanings.
#   - e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v) — get one entity by id or compound key (examples below use `v=$`, not concrete API values).
#   - Use TSV `plasm_expr` shapes exactly, substituting concrete values for placeholders.
#   - For compound-key forms such as `e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v)`, keep keyed args (`p#=v` / `name=value`); never rewrite them as positional.
#   - e#{p#=v, …} — list query; `e#` alone queries all.
#   - e#(id).p# — relation. e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..) — method call.
#   - For list/query goals, use brace predicates `e#{p#=v, …}`. Use dotted `e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..)` only when the goal asks to mutate or call a method.
#   - e#.m#(args) — standalone create/action (no anchor id needed).
#   - e#(id)[p#,…] — non-empty scalar subset. Dot after `e#(id)` means relations or taught `m#`, not scalar fields.
#   - **Bracket render / synthesis** (`label[p#,…] <<TAG … TAG` after projection): heredoc body is **Minijinja** with `rows` (projected row dicts). Use `{% for r in rows %}…{% endfor %}`, `{{ r.p15 }}`, `{{ rows | length }}` as needed. The rendered **`content`** may be **any** textual format (plain text, markdown, HTML fragments, structured snippets, JSON **text**, logs—not markdown-specific); guard accidental Jinja tokens with `{% raw %}…{% endraw %}`. Output is one synthetic row shaped like `{"content": "…"}` — for **string**/body parameters use **`binding.content`**, not bare **`binding`**.
#   - To list X scoped by parent Y, use `X{p#=AnchorEntity(id)}` from X's rows; do not invent `Y(id).p#`.
#   - `[v, …]` — array value inside method args, e.g. `p#=[e#($)]`.
#   - Plain `str` values use double quotes. In quoted strings only `\"` and `\\` are escapes.
#   - `select` chooses one listed allowed value; `multiselect` chooses zero or more as `[v, …]`.
#   - `p#`-only rows predeclare slots; they are metadata, not expressions to output.
#   - `$` is only a fill-in cue. Substitute a real value; never send `$`.
# - `..` — optional params may follow (`optional params:` lists them, comma-separated). `..` can appear alone when all args are optional.
#   - TSV rows are teaching rows. `plasm_expr` teaches syntax; `Meaning` teaches selection and argument semantics.
#

plasm_expr	Meaning
p2	str · Type name (unique key)
p1	int · Numeric type identifier
p3	str · API resource URL
e1($)[p2,p1,p3]	returns e1 · An elemental type (Fire, Water, etc.)
e1	returns [e1] · List all elemental types
e1($).p4	returns Generation · Generation this type was introduced
e1($).p5	returns MoveDamageClass · Default damage class for this type
e1($).p6	returns [Move] · Moves of this elemental type
e1($).p7	returns [Pokemon] · Pokémon with this type
